We recommended that Management:

Adhere to the general process of handling and accounting for inventories and supplies and materials as prescribed by the MNGAS for LGUs;

Stop the procurement of supplies per department instead purchase supplies and materials needed for the quarter based on the approved annual procurement plan through DBM Procurement Service or through public bidding;

Advise the GSO to maintain stock cards and record deliveries and issuances therein;

Advise the GSO to document each issuance of inventory using the RIS form;

Advise the GSO to regularly prepare the SSMI and forward the same to the Accounting Unit to serve as basis in the preparation of JEV and recording of issuances;

Advise the Accounting Unit to account for the inventories using the perpetual inventory method; and

Regularly conduct an annual physical inventory count and reconcile the same with the records of the accounting and the GSO.

We recommended that Management:

Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct physical inventory of all properties owned by the LGU and render report thereon within the prescribed period; 


Instruct the GSO to prepare and maintain property cards;


Require the GSO to prepare an updated list of accountable officers and update the PAR every three years or every time there is a change of accountable officer;

Require the Inventory Committee to identify all unserviceable properties and undertake the necessary procedures to dispose them; 

Adopt and implement the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances by issuing the necessary Office Order to personnel who shall conduct the same; and

Closely monitor the implementation of the one-time cleansing of the PPE account balances.

We recommended that Management:

Instruct the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of public infrastructures especially the local road networks and submit the RPCLRN to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of the ensuing year;

Instruct the GSO to periodically render a Report on Local Road Network, and furnish copies to the concerned offices; 

Instruct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;


Require the GSO and the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain property cards and ledger cards, respectively;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to disclosed the Road Network System in the Notes to the Financial Statement in conformity with the prescribed format; and

Ensure coordination among LGU offices represented by the Municipal Accountant, GSO and Municipal Engineer to properly implement the accounting and reporting guidelines on the Local Roads Asset Management System.

We recommended that Management:  

Instruct the Municipal Engineer to submit the necessary documents to support the demolition of the Senior Citizen Building for evaluation;

Instruct the GSO, in coordination with the Municipal Engineer, to recover the waste materials arising from the demolition of the said building and document the disposal, either through sale or destruction, using the WMR;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to derecognize from the books the cost of the demolished building through preparation of JEV duly supported with the required documents; and

Strictly observe the rules and regulations in the disposal of government properties.

