We recommended that the Local Chief Executive to undertake the following courses of actions.                                                                                                                                                                                                1.Direct the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator and the Municipal Engineer , together with the Municipal Budget Officer in coordination with the Local Development Council  shall include in the Annual Investment Program only feasible projects  which can be implemented within the target date of completion with the proposed budget allocation, subject to the budgeting and other applicable standards for planning and thorough identification and proper scheduling of all related tasks in carrying out projects; to regularly monitor the status of project implementation in order to introduce the necessary interventions at the earliest time should there be any noted lapses during the implementation stage;

2.Instruct the BAC and the Municipal Engineer in coordination with the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator to undertake the necessary steps for adequate planning of resources and proper scheduling of procurement activities to pave way for timely completion of the projects within the approved time and schedule.

3. Convene the Municipal Development Council in order to review all projects that remain unimplemented and determine whether the same can be implemented in the succeeding year. .Likewise, consider the option to cause immediate realignment or reversion in the unappropriated surplus of the general fund for re-appropriation to other development projects of unutilized funds that are derived from savings from completed projects and all projects which are no longer needed for inclusion in the Annual Investment Program in the next budget preparation.

We recommended to the Management the following courses of actions:
1. To conduct periodic public information and education campaign, through the Local Solid Waste Management Board, to encourage social awareness in the implementation of the Solid Waste Management Plan of the Local Government Unit to avoid environmental concerns and health issues in the future.

2. To encourage the Barangays to activate the LSWMB to perform its functions and responsibilities as provided for in Section 6, Rule VI of the Act, to wit:

a) Formulate solid waste management program consistent with city/municipality plan;
b) Segregation and collection of biodegradable, compostable, reusable wastes;
c) Establish materials recovery facility;
d) Allocate barangay funds; look for sources of funds;
e) Organize core coordinators; and
f) Submit monthly report to the city or municipality.

3.Strict implementation of the LSWMB on the operation of MRF, particularly on the following activities:

a) Proper  segregation of waste;
b) The incessant utilization of MRF to minimize the volume of wastes to be transported for disposal;
c) The recording of waste received transferred; and
d) The implementation of fines and penalties to those violating the Municipal Ordinance No. 110.

4. Strict implementation on the operation of the CD, particularly on the following activities:

a) The daily recording of waste received and disposed;
b) The perimeter fencing to prevent roaming animals from scouring for food at the dumped wastes; and
c) The conduct of daily covering of soil on the disposed wastes.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Engineer to:
Prepare and submit the Program of Work and Detailed Cost Estimate including the labor component of all programs/projects/activities (PPAs) charged to the 20 percent development fund;
Indicate the Contract Time or Duration of the project;
Identify the specific PPAs to which the labor cost was attributed and submit the Certificate of Project Completion of all projects of the Municipality implemented by administration.

We recommended and the Management agreed to require the Municipal Accountant to:
a. record income and expenses in the Trust Fund books upon utilization of funds received from national agencies or any other sources as well as from trust liability for unspent disaster fund from previous years that are considered as non-exchange transactions;
b. prepare and submit for succeeding years the Statement of Financial Performance for the Trust Fund along with the other financial statements of the Municipality.

We recommended and the Management agreed to require the Municipal Accountant to submit the following:
 a. Tax Returns (Annual Income Tax Return of the preceding tax year) or Business Tax Returns (Value Added Tax or Percentage Tax Return covering the previous six months) and original copy of Omnibus Sworn Statement (OSS) and Mayor’s Permit of the suppliers for those transactions above P500,000.00;
 b. Posting of Notice of Award in GPPB Online Portal for information purposes;
 c. Purchase Order (PO) for the 300 (25kls) of rice procured from Bueno Rice Store under Check No. 72109 dated April 7, 2020, indicating therein the kind of rice that was purchased;
 The Management was also required to ensure completeness of procurement documents and contracts are in order before accepting deliveries.

We recommended the Management to require the:
 a. General Services Officer (GSO) to prepare and maintain road networks property cards and Report on Local Road Network based on the report submitted by the Municipal Engineer;
